STEP 2: ARCHITECTURE EXPLANATION
-----------------------------------------------

"Let me walk you through the architecture."

SAY THIS:
"I followed a 3-tier architecture with clear separation of concerns.

The FIRST tier is the Presentation Layer — two React applications built 
with Vite. The customer frontend runs on port 5173, and the admin panel 
runs on port 5174. Both communicate with the backend through Axios 
HTTP calls.

The SECOND tier is the Business Logic Layer — an Express.js REST API 
running on port 4000. It has four route modules: /user for authentication, 
/product for catalog management, /cart for shopping cart operations, and 
/order for checkout and payments. Every protected route goes through 
JWT middleware before reaching the controller.

The THIRD tier is the Data Layer — MongoDB Atlas for persistent storage, 
Cloudinary CDN for product images, and Stripe/Razorpay APIs for payment 
processing."

IF ASKED WHY THIS ARCHITECTURE:
"Separation of concerns means I can scale each tier independently. 
If traffic increases, I can add more backend instances without touching 
the frontend. Having the admin panel as a separate app also improves 
security — admin functionality is completely isolated."


-----------------------------------------------
STEP 3: WHEN THEY ASK ABOUT SPECIFIC FEATURES
-----------------------------------------------

----- AUTHENTICATION -----
"For authentication, I implemented a stateless JWT-based system. 

When a user registers, the password goes through bcrypt with a salt 
factor of 10 — this produces a one-way hash that's deliberately slow 
to compute, making brute-force attacks impractical.

Then I generate a JWT containing the user's MongoDB ObjectId and return 
it to the frontend. The frontend stores it in localStorage and sends 
it in the request header for every subsequent API call.

On the backend, I have an auth middleware that intercepts every protected 
request, verifies the JWT using the secret key, extracts the userId, 
and injects it into the request body so that downstream controllers 
know which user is making the request.

For admin routes, I use a separate adminAuth middleware with a different 
token structure — admin token is created by signing the concatenation of 
admin email and password. This gives me role-based access control with 
two distinct middleware chains."


----- DATABASE -----
"For the database, I chose MongoDB with Mongoose ODM for three reasons:
First, e-commerce products have varying attributes — different sizes, 
categories, multiple images — and MongoDB's flexible schema handles this 
without needing ALTER TABLE statements.
Second, the cart data is naturally a nested object — product ID maps to 
size maps to quantity — which fits perfectly in a document store.
Third, MongoDB Atlas gives me managed hosting with automatic backups."


----- CART SYSTEM -----
"The cart uses a nested hashmap data structure stored inside the user 
document. The structure is: product ID as key, with an inner object 
mapping size to quantity.

For example: { 'product123': { 'M': 2, 'L': 1 } }

This gives O(1) time complexity for add, update, and lookup operations — 
compared to O(n) if I had used an array. I embedded the cart in the 
user document because they're always accessed together, eliminating 
the need for a separate query or JOIN operation."


----- PAYMENTS -----
"I integrated three payment methods: Cash on Delivery, Stripe, and 
Razorpay.

For Stripe, I use a redirect-based flow. When the user chooses Stripe, 
the backend creates a Checkout Session with line items and delivery 
charges, then returns the session URL. The frontend redirects to 
Stripe's hosted checkout page. After payment, Stripe redirects back 
to my /verify page with success status and order ID. The verify page 
calls my backend to confirm and mark the order as paid.

For Razorpay, I use a modal-based flow. The backend creates a Razorpay 
order, returns the order object, and the frontend opens Razorpay's 
payment modal right on the same page. On successful payment, the 
handler function calls my verification endpoint, which fetches the 
order status from Razorpay's API to confirm it's 'paid'.

The key design decision was creating the order in the database FIRST 
with payment set to false, then updating it after verification. This 
handles edge cases where the user's browser crashes during payment — 
we can still track and reconcile the order."


----- IMAGE UPLOADS -----
"For product images, I built a pipeline using Multer and Cloudinary.
When an admin uploads images, Multer temporarily stores them on disk 
using its disk storage engine. Then I upload all images to Cloudinary 
in parallel using Promise.all(), which returns secure HTTPS CDN URLs. 
These URLs are stored in the product's image array in MongoDB.

This approach has three advantages: CDN delivery from edge servers, 
automatic image optimization, and separation of media from database."


-----------------------------------------------
STEP 4: WHEN THEY ASK ABOUT FRONTEND
-----------------------------------------------

"For the frontend, I used React 18 with Vite as the build tool — 
Vite provides significantly faster hot module replacement compared 
to Create React App.

For state management, I used the React Context API with a ShopContext 
provider that wraps the entire app. It manages products, cart items, 
authentication token, search state, and exposes helper functions like 
addToCart and getCartAmount.

I implemented optimistic updates — when a user adds to cart, I update 
the local state immediately for instant visual feedback, then sync 
with the backend asynchronously. This gives the user a smooth, lag-free 
experience.

For routing, I used React Router v6 with 12 client-side routes. The 
product detail page uses dynamic routing with useParams() to extract 
the product ID from the URL. The payment verification page uses 
useSearchParams() to read callback parameters from Stripe.

For styling, I used Tailwind CSS with a mobile-first responsive approach. 
The layout adapts across four breakpoints — mobile, small tablet, 
tablet, and desktop."


-----------------------------------------------
STEP 5: CLOSING (What would you improve?)
-----------------------------------------------

"If I were to take this project further, I would add three things:

First, Redis caching for the product listing endpoint to reduce database 
queries on frequently accessed data.

Second, Webhook-based payment verification instead of client-side 
redirects — webhooks are more reliable because they work even if the 
user closes the browser mid-payment.

Third, input sanitization middleware using express-validator to prevent 
NoSQL injection attacks, and rate limiting to prevent API abuse."


